  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The research on a fluorogenic complementation toolkit for investigating lipid droplet-organelle interactions has garnered significant attention, with 25 citations since its posting on bioRxiv. This preprint has successfully transitioned to a formal publication in the Journal of Cell Biology, reflecting its influence in the field and its importance in understanding cellular dynamics.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This study presents a novel fluorogenic complementation tool kit aimed at probing lipid droplet-organelle interactions, a critical aspect of cellular organization and function. Initially shared as a preprint on bioRxiv, the work has received 25 citations, indicative of its relevance and impact on current research. Following its successful peer review, it was formally published in the Journal of Cell Biology, where it has accumulated an additional 21 citations to date. This trajectory underscores the work's substantial reception within the academic community.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The authors are affiliated with esteemed institutions, including St. Jude Children's Research Hospital and the Howard Hughes Medical Institute, adding credibility to their research contributions. The geographical diversity of the top citing countries, which includes France, Italy, the United Kingdom, the United States, and Germany, reflects the broad international interest in the findings and methodologies presented in this research.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Moreover, this toolkit allows for innovative approaches in studying lipid droplets and their interactions with various organelles, potentially opening new avenues for understanding lipid metabolism and related cellular processes. The downstream reuse of this research materials exceeds 27 occurrences, showcasing its utility and impact in facilitating subsequent studies in this evolving field.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The formulation and early sharing of this preprint exemplify a commitment to open science, allowing the broader research community to engage with and build upon their findings prior to formal publication. This proactive approach fosters immediate community dialogue and enhances the overall scientific discourse surrounding lipid droplet research. The authors' work is crucial in driving forward the understanding of cellular mechanics in health and disease contexts.</p>",
